'''''Lobster''''' is a French [[novella]] by Guillaume Lecasble. It was published in Paris by Les [[Éditions du Seuil]] in 2003, and has been translated into English and Spanish.

==Reception==

[[Nicholas Lezard]], in ''[[The Guardian]]'', said of the English translation: "there was a Lobster-shaped hole in world literature which has now been neatly filled by this remarkable work".<ref>{{cite news|last=Lezard|first=Nicholas|title=Cooked to perfection|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/jul/09/featuresreviews.guardianreview33|newspaper=The Guardian|date=9 July 2005}}</ref> In ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', [[Sam Leith]] put it in a list of 'Mad Stuff'.<ref>{{cite news|last=Leith|first=Sam|title=Mad Stuff|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3648493/Mad-stuff.html|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=5 December 2005}}</ref> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' called it a "brief, bizarre, boiling broth of surrealism, romantic fatalism and slapstick",<ref>{{cite journal|title=An erotic shellfish fable.|journal=Kirkus Reviews|date=1 Nov 2005|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/guillaume-lecasble/lobster/}}</ref> and ''Publisher's Weekly'' said it was "both tender and appalling".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Lobster|journal=Publishers Weekly|date=10 October 2005}}</ref>

